UML:TaggedValue.value: The GeoSciML Borehole package contains model elements for representing Boreholes. This is primarily through re-use of standard components from the (external) Observations and Measurements package.
The GeoSciML Borehole package contains model elements for representing Boreholes. This is primarily through re-use of standard components from the (external) Observations and Measurements package.

In the context of GeoSciML, this will typically be a GeologicFeature, such as a geologic unit. If the SamplingFeature samples multiple features (e.g. borehole, traverse) (i) if it is a sequence of units, then the part/GeologicUnitPart mechanisms may be used, (ii) else if it is an informal collection that exists only because of the sampling, then multiple sampledFeature roles should be used
Might be a borehole or observation well, or a traverse or flightline

A Borehole Collar is a feature corresponding to the start point of a borehole. These are often plotted on a map. If a text descripiton of the location is available, which should be placed in the gml:description for that feature. If no GM_Point is available, URN:CGI:unknown should be used Implementers delivering 3-D collar locations should provide and elevation to improve interoperability.

Compromise approach to supply elevation explictly for location; this is to allow for software that cannot process 3-D GM_Point. Use null if elevation is unknown. Direct position shall have a dimension of 1, and CRS will be a "vertical" CRS (e.g. EPSG CRSs in the range 5600-5799).
One end of the GM_Curve that defines the shape Usually the point at a surface where drilling started.
The hole that has this collar for its start point
A special kind of Mapped Feature whose shape is 1-D (a curve)
Links to 1-D MappedFeature instances that are logged (interpreted) intervals within a borehole. This requirement is common in geoscience boreholes
drilling started from a natural topographic surface
Drilling started from the wall of an open pit or quarry
Drilling started from an underground location, such as a driveway, chamber or open-stope
New drill hole spudded off the wall of an existing hole
Might be a well-log or borehole-log
A borehole is the generalized term for any narrow shaft drilled in the ground, either vertically or horizontally.

In the context of GeoSciML, this will typically be a GeologicFeature, such as a geologic unit. If the SamplingFeature samples multiple features (e.g. borehole, traverse) (i) if it is a sequence of units, then the part/GeologicUnitPart mechanisms may be used, (ii) else if it is an informal collection that exists only because of the sampling, then multiple sampledFeature roles should be used
This relation might point to specimens retrieved from a hole or traverse or outcrop, or to a set of holes from the same campaign
Might be a borehole or observation well, or a traverse or flightline

SamplingFeatureCollection is the class to use for representing geoscience field data collected at an outcrop, e.g. geologic unit descriptions, fault description, contact description, structural measurements, specimens. SamplingFeatureCollection might also be used to represent dredge hauls, measured sections, and other sorts of sampling features with multiple kinds of associated observations.
The date on which drilling of the borehole commenced
The organisation responsible for drilling the borehole (as opposed to commissioning the borehole)
Indicates the drilling method used. Appropriate terms would include Rotary; Shell & Auger; Downhole Air Hammer; Hand Auger etc
Indicates the inclination of the borehole. Appropriate terms would include vertical; inclined up; inclined down, horizontal
Organisation responsible for commissioning the borehole (as opposed to drilling the borehole)
Indicates the position relative to ground surface where the borehole commenced. Appropriate terms would include Drilled from Ground Surface; Drilled Underground; Drilled from Quarry Floor etc
Interval(s) within the borehole from which core was recovered Use GM_Envelope with 1-D CRS corresponding to borehole curve shape
Organisation that is custodian of the core recovered from the borehole
This relation might point to specimens retrieved from a hole or traverse or outcrop, or to a set of holes from the same campaign
Might be a well-log or borehole-log
